 view. Four distinguished scholars in the field examine the Constitution, the two-party system, the division of power between state and federal governments, and other major features of the American political system in terms of how they differ from other democracies, and they explore what those differences ultimately mean for democratic performance. By merging two important fields of study, American government and comparative political systems, this essential text offers a new and refreshingly insightful view of American exceptionalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh1 aGrofman, Bernard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLijphart, Arend, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aShugart, Matthew Soberg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019808940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021070540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300210705423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300210705/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY